Ask HN: Why do static sites need to be generated on the server?
text:
I'm in the process of building a Hugo site, and I'm at the point where I'm looking for deployment options.

My assumption was that I'd mostly be looking at fancy ways of just pushing my /public folder to a server. I run Hugo commands locally, maybe I push to a git repo, and that triggers a push of my public folder.

Instead, I'm typically being instructed to .gitignore my /public folder, push everything to a server (sometimes via a git repo), and then allow the server to run it's own build command and then deploy?

Can someone help me understand the benefits of building the static site on the server as well? Certainly it can't just be for URLs because that seems like a problem solved easier in other ways.

Ask HN: Referrals for Private Businesses?
text:
I run a small farm that I want to keep private. I do not want to sell to the public; instead, I want to cultivate a small group of loyal customers that participate in a CSA (community supported agriculture) program and enjoy some other perks (eg. stocked fishing ponds, miles of hiking trails, camp sites, music concerts, etc.).

Since I want to keep everything private, I am at a loss for how to find customers beyond a word-of-mouth referral scheme (e.g. 5% off your annual membership for every new member that you bring to us). While I think this would eventually work, I am not sure how to bootstrap that model.

I figure that someone here on HN been down this sort of road, as I feel it is not far off from the notion of finding local investors for a startup company that needs to remain in stealth mode.

Is there a good solution to my bootstrap problem, perhaps used by tech startups? (Is there an app for that?) Anyone solved this problem (perhaps without tech) in a way that I might want to consider and emulate?

Ask HN: If metaverse HN existed, would you hang out here?
text:
Let's say the admittedly somewhat shallow version of meta's vision of the future plays out.

In that future, a Hacker News space in the metaverse opens up and enough people have hardware to utilize it. Imagine a log cabin nestled in fourier trees next a river of 1s and 0s (or just a regular log cabin in a regular forest next to a babbling brook).

Would you hang out there? Wait to see what people discussed? Chat about stories of the day? Take in the sights?

Ask HN: Since when did 2FA become 3FA?
text:
When did Google stop trusting 2FA? I have email accounts that have Google Authenticator codes.

Now when I sign into them, after I enter my 2FA code it'll ask me for a 3rd factor - it'll ask me "Verify it's you. Google wants to make sure it's really you trying to access" and then I have to do something with an email address or phone number.

How can I permanently disable that?

I want 2FA, not unexpected 3FA...
